Strength of Linear Relationships

Age v. Distance

What is the effect of age on maximum legibility distance of a road sign?

Qualitative description:

  • a negative, moderately strong linear relationship

Quantitative measures:

  • correlation
  • linear regression

Correlation

We will:

  • give a definition of the correlation \( r \)
  • discuss the calculation of \( r \)
  • explain how to interpret the value of \( r \), and
  • talk about some of the properties of \( r \).

Correlation: Defined

To quote (p. 49):

The correlation coefficient \( r \) is a numerical measure that measures the strength and direction of a linear relationship between two quantitative variables.

  • Can correlation measure of a curvelinear relationship? No

  • Can two categorical variables be correlated with one another? No

Correlation: Calculated

Let

  • \( y_i \) be the \( i^{th} \) obs. of the response variable
  • \( \bar{y} \) be the mean of the response variable
  • \( S_y \) the standard deviation of the response variable

Similarly let \( x_i \), \( \bar{x} \), and \( S_x \) be defined for the explanatory variable. The correlation is:

\[ r = \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^n \left( \frac{x_i - \bar{x}}{S_x} \right) \left( \frac{y_i - \bar{y}}{S_y} \right) \]

Correlation: Calculated

\[ r = \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^n \left( \frac{x_i - \bar{x}}{S_x} \right) \left( \frac{y_i - \bar{y}}{S_y} \right) \]

  • This is more of a pain to calculate than the the standard deviation!
  • No one calculates it by hand
  • In this class, you
    • will learn the properties of \( r \)
    • how to interpret it, and
    • how to calculate it with R.

Correlation: Properties

\[ r = \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^n \left( \frac{x_i - \bar{x}}{S_x} \right) \left( \frac{y_i - \bar{y}}{S_y} \right) \]

  • A correlation between age in years and distance in feet has what units?

    • \( x_i - \bar{x} \) units of years
    • \( S_x \) units of years
    • \( \frac{x_i - \bar{x}}{S_x} := \frac{\text{years}}{\text{years}} := \text{unitless} \)

  • Changing the units (feet to inches) or (years to days) does not affect the correlation.

Correlation: Properties

\[ \begin{aligned} r & = \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^n \left( \frac{x_i - \bar{x}}{S_x} \right) \left( \frac{y_i - \bar{y}}{S_y} \right) \\ S_x & = \sqrt{ \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^n \left(x_i - \bar{x}\right)^2 } \end{aligned} \]

  • You can prove that:

    • \( -1 \le r \le 1 \)
    • \( |r| = 1 \) if and only if \( y = a + xb \)

  • \( r \) near zero implies a weak linear relationship

Correlation: Examples

From Wikipedia's page on correlation:

  • Warning: Wikipedia defines correlation more broadly then Stat 202 does.

Correlation: Outliers

Outliers can either

  • increase the value of the correlation
  • decrease the value of the correlation

If an outlier follows the (linear!) pattern it will…

  • increase the value of the correlation

If an outlier breaks the (linear!) pattern it will…

  • decrease the value of the correlation

See p. 51 for an interactive demo.

Quantifying a linear relationship

  • Correlation measures the strength of a linear relationship.

  • Linear regression describes the specifics of a linear relationship

    • one of the most important statistical techniques
    • widely used and abused

Linear regression concepts

Any line can be written as: \[ y = a + bx \] where

  • \( x \) explanatory variable
  • \( y \) response variable
  • \( a \) is the intercept
  • \( b \) is the slope
  • (if this is unfamiliar see bottom of p. 53 for an algebra review)

How do we pick the best line for a given set of data?

Age v. distance: n=6

Many possible lines

Minimize vertical distance

By minimizing the area of the squares

Aside: Least-Squares regression

  • Gauss-Markov theorem states that least squares regression lines are the best possible regression lines under a wide variety of conditions

    • (proof requires post high school math)

  • Stat 202 covers two variable \( Q \rightarrow Q \) regression

    • ignore the formulas for \( a \) and \( b \) on p. 54

  • Stat 202 does not not cover multi-variable regression (most common)

Least-Squares regression

Predicting gestation (in days) from the longevity (in years) of a given animal.

head(animals)

        animal gestation longevity
1       baboon       187        20
2   bear-black       219        18
3 bear-grizzly       225        25
4   bear-polar       240        20
5       beaver       122         5
6      buffalo       278        15

Gestation related to longevity?

plot( 
 gestation ~ longevity, 
 xlab="Longevity (years)",
 ylab="Gestation (days)",
 data=animals)
  • read ~ as by
    • gestation by longevity
  • read xlab as x label
  • read ylab as y label
  • read data as data

Describe the plot

Direction, form and strength?

  • positive linear moderate

Break or Keep pattern outliers?

  • one keep pattern
  • elephant

Calculating Correlation

cor( animals$gestation, 
     animals$longevity )

0.6632
  • read cor as correlation
  • read $ as column
    • animals column gestation
    • animals column longevity

Least squares regression in R

## Fit a least squares model and save
## it to the new variable 'animal.lm'
animal.lm <- lm( 
  gestation ~ longevity, data=animals ) 

## Pull out the 'a' and 'b' values
coef(animal.lm)

(Intercept)   longevity 
      21.71       13.13

\[ y = a + x b \]

  • (Intercept) is \( a \)
  • longevity is \( b \)

Plotting the regression line

## As before
plot( 
 gestation ~ longevity, 
 xlab="Longevity (years)",
 ylab="Gestation (days)",
 data=animals)

## Ad line
abline(animal.lm )

Predicting w/ a regression line

Gestation of an animal with 35 years longevity? 

coef( animal.lm ) 

(Intercept)   longevity 
      21.71       13.13

\[ \begin{aligned} y & = a + b x \\ & = 21.71 + 13.13 \times 35 \\ & = 481.26 \end{aligned} \]

Predicting w/ a regression line

Gestation of an animal with 80 years longevity?

\[ \begin{aligned} y & = 21.71 + 13.13 x \\ & = 21.71 + 13.13 \times 80 \\ & = 1072.11 \end{aligned} \]

Is this extrapolation a good idea?

  • No do not predict outside of your data!
  • human gestation \( \approx \) 268 days

Correlation and Causation

  • http://xkcd.com/552/

More generally association does not imply causation.

$$\text{Association for } C \rightarrow C $$

Are patients in Hospital A more likely to die than patients in Hospital B?

$$\text{Association for } C \rightarrow C $$

  • Looks bad for Hospital A

$$\text{Association for } C \rightarrow C $$

$$\text{Association for } C \rightarrow C $$

Simpson's paradox

  • Ignoring illness severity suggested Hospital B was better
  • In fact, Hospital A is always better
  • a lurking variable reversed the association

Causality Summary

Association does not imply causation

  • High correlation does not imply causation
  • Simpson's paradox can bite you on categorical data

All is not lost…

  • experiments let us make causal claims (next lecture)
  • econometric tools give causalality in non-experimental data (not covered)
